  <h1>What to do, WHEN</h1>
  
  <H3>1. Fever</H3>
  <ul>
    <li>Get plenty of rest to allow your body to recover and fight off the infection causing your fever.</li>
    <li>Stay hydrated: Drink plenty of fluids, such as water or electrolyte-rich drinks, to prevent dehydration.</li>
    <li>Monitor your temperature: Keep track of your temperature with a thermometer and take note of any changes or trends.</li>
    <li>Manage your symptoms: Use over-the-counter medications such as acetaminophen (Tylenol) or ibuprofen (Advil) to help reduce fever and relieve other symptoms such as headache, body aches, and chills.</li>
    <li>Seek medical attention: If your fever persists or becomes high, or if you have other concerning symptoms such as shortness of breath, chest pain, or confusion, seek medical attention right away.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>It is also important to practice good hygiene to prevent the spread of illness to others. Cover your mouth and nose when coughing or sneezing, wash your hands frequently, and avoid close contact with others until you are feeling better.</p>
  
  <hr style="background-color: black;">

  <h3>2. Influenza (the flu)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Get vaccinated: Getting an annual flu vaccine is the most effective way to prevent the flu. The vaccine is typically available in the fall and can be administered by a healthcare professional.</li>
    <li>Wash your hands frequently: Use soap and water to wash your hands for at least 20 seconds, especially after coughing or sneezing, and before eating or touching your face</li>
    <li>Cover your mouth and nose: Cover your mouth and nose with a tissue when coughing or sneezing, and dispose of the tissue in the trash. If you don't have a tissue, cough or sneeze into your elbow instead of your hands.</li>
    <li>Avoid close contact: Stay away from people who are sick, and avoid close contact with others if you are sick.</li>
    <li>Clean and disinfect surfaces: Clean and disinfect frequently touched surfaces such as doorknobs, countertops, and phones.</li>
    <li>Stay home if you're sick: If you have symptoms of the flu, stay home from work or school until you are feeling better to prevent spreading the virus to others.</li>
  </ul>
    <p>By taking these precautions, you can help protect yourself and others from the flu. If you do become sick with the flu, be sure to follow your healthcare provider's recommendations for treatment and self-care.</p>


  <h3>3. Common cold</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Wash your hands frequently: Use soap and water to wash your hands for at least 20 seconds, especially before eating or touching your face.</li>
    <li>Cover your mouth and nose: Cover your mouth and nose with a tissue when coughing or sneezing, and dispose of the tissue in the trash. If you don't have a tissue, cough or sneeze into your elbow instead of your hands.</li>
    <li>Avoid close contact: Stay away from people who are sick, and avoid close contact with others if you are sick</li>
    <li>Clean and disinfect surfaces: Clean and disinfect frequently touched surfaces such as doorknobs, countertops, and phones</li>
    <li>Practice good hygiene: Avoid touching your eyes, nose, and mouth, which can help prevent the spread of germs.</li>
    <li>Stay home if you're sick: If you have symptoms of the common cold, stay home from work or school until you are feeling better to prevent spreading the virus to others.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>By taking these precautions, you can help protect yourself and others from the common cold. If you do become sick with the common cold, be sure to rest, drink plenty of fluids, and take over-the-counter medications such as acetaminophen (Tylenol) or ibuprofen (Advil) to relieve symptoms.</p>

  <h3>4. COVID-19</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Get vaccinated: Vaccination is the most effective way to prevent COVID-19. You should get vaccinated as soon as possible if you are eligible.</li>
    <li>Wear a mask: Wear a mask that covers your nose and mouth when you are in public or around others who are not in your household</li>
    <li>Wash your hands frequently: Use soap and water to wash your hands for at least 20 seconds, especially after being in public, coughing or sneezing, and before touching your face</li>
    <li>Practice physical distancing: Stay at least 6 feet (2 meters) away from others who are not in your household.</li>
    <li>Avoid crowds: Avoid large gatherings, especially indoors where the risk of transmission is higher.</li>
    <li>Ventilate indoor spaces: Open windows and doors or use an air purifier to increase ventilation in indoor spaces</li>
    <li>Cover your mouth and nose: Cover your mouth and nose with a tissue when coughing or sneezing, and dispose of the tissue in the trash. If you don't have a tissue, cough or sneeze into your elbow instead of your hands.</li>
    <li>Clean and disinfect surfaces: Clean and disinfect frequently touched surfaces such as doorknobs, countertops, and phones.</li>
    <li>Stay home if you're sick: If you have symptoms of COVID-19 or have been in close contact with someone who has tested positive, stay home and follow the guidance of your healthcare provider and public health officials.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>By taking these precautions, you can help protect yourself and others from COVID-19. If you do become sick with COVID-19, be sure to follow your healthcare provider's recommendations for treatment and self-care, and isolate yourself to prevent spreading the virus to others.</p>

  <h3>5. Diabetes</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Control your blood sugar: Check your blood sugar levels regularly, take your medications as prescribed, and follow a healthy eating plan to control your blood sugar levels</li>
    <li>Exercise regularly: Regular physical activity can help control your blood sugar levels, improve your overall health, and reduce your risk of complications.</li>
    <li>Eat a healthy diet: Follow a healthy eating plan that includes plenty of fruits, vegetables, whole grains, lean protein, and healthy fats to help control your blood sugar levels.</li>
    <li>Monitor your feet: Check your feet daily for cuts, blisters, sores, or changes in color or temperature, and see a healthcare provider if you notice any problems.</li>
    <li>Get regular check-ups: See your healthcare provider regularly to monitor your blood sugar levels, blood pressure, cholesterol, and other health markers.</li>
    <li>Manage stress: Stress can affect your blood sugar levels, so it's important to find ways to manage stress, such as through exercise, relaxation techniques, or counseling.</li>
    <li>Quit smoking: Smoking can increase your risk of complications, so if you smoke, consider quitting.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>By taking these precautions, you can help manage your diabetes and reduce your risk of complications. It's also important to work closely with your healthcare provider to develop a personalized plan for managing your diabetes</p>

  <h3>6. Cardiovascular disease</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Control your blood pressure: High blood pressure is a major risk factor for cardiovascular disease, so it's important to monitor your blood pressure regularly and take steps to keep it under control, such as through medication, diet, and exercise.</li>
    <li>Control your cholesterol: High cholesterol levels can contribute to cardiovascular disease, so it's important to have your cholesterol levels checked regularly and take steps to lower them if they are high, such as through medication, diet, and exercise.</li>
    <li>Follow a healthy diet: A heart-healthy diet can help reduce the risk of cardiovascular disease. This includes eating plenty of fruits, vegetables, whole grains, lean protein, and healthy fats, and limiting saturated and trans fats, salt, and added sugars.</li>
    <li>Exercise regularly: Regular physical activity can help improve your heart health, reduce your risk of complications, and improve your overall health. Aim for at least 150 minutes of moderate-intensity exercise per week.</li>
    <li>Manage stress: Stress can contribute to cardiovascular disease, so it's important to find ways to manage stress, such as through exercise, relaxation techniques, or counseling.</li>
    <li>Quit smoking: Smoking is a major risk factor for cardiovascular disease, so if you smoke, consider quitting.</li>
    <li>Follow your healthcare provider's recommendations: Work closely with your healthcare provider to develop a personalized plan for managing your cardiovascular disease, and follow their recommendations for medication, lifestyle changes, and other treatments.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>By taking these precautions, you can help manage your cardiovascular disease and reduce the risk of complications. It's important to work closely with your healthcare provider to develop a personalized plan for managing your condition.</p>

  <h3>7. Cancer</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Follow your treatment plan: Follow your healthcare provider's recommendations for treatment, including medications, chemotherapy, radiation therapy, and surgery.</li>
    <li>Manage symptoms: If you experience symptoms such as pain, nausea, fatigue, or other side effects of treatment, talk to your healthcare provider about ways to manage them.</li>
    <li>Eat a healthy diet: A healthy diet can help support your overall health and improve your quality of life during cancer treatment. Talk to your healthcare provider or a registered dietitian about a healthy eating plan that's right for you.</li>
    <li>Stay physically active: Regular physical activity can help reduce fatigue and improve your quality of life during cancer treatment. Talk to your healthcare provider about safe and appropriate exercise options for you.</li>
    <li>Manage stress: Stress can affect your overall health and well-being, so it's important to find ways to manage stress, such as through exercise, relaxation techniques, or counseling.</li>
    <li>Quit smoking: Smoking can increase the risk of complications and make cancer treatment less effective, so if you smoke, consider quitting.</li>
    <li>Attend follow-up appointments: Attend all follow-up appointments with your healthcare provider to monitor your cancer and address any concerns.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>By taking these precautions, you can help manage your cancer and reduce the risk of complications. It's important to work closely with your healthcare provider to develop a personalized plan for managing your cancer.</p>

  <h3>8. Mental health disorders</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Get enough sleep: Good quality sleep is essential for good mental health, so aim for 7-8 hours of sleep per night.</li>
    <li>Exercise regularly: Regular physical activity can help reduce stress, anxiety, and depression, and improve overall mental health. Aim for at least 150 minutes of moderate-intensity exercise per week.</li>
    <li>Eat a healthy diet: A healthy diet can help support good mental health. Aim for a balanced diet that includes plenty of fruits, vegetables, whole grains, lean protein, and healthy fats.</li>
    <li>Manage stress: Stress can contribute to the development of mental health disorders, so it's important to find ways to manage stress, such as through exercise, relaxation techniques, or counseling.</li>
    <li>Avoid alcohol and drugs: Substance abuse can contribute to the development of mental health disorders, so it's important to avoid alcohol and drugs or use them in moderation.</li>
    <li>Connect with others: Social support is important for good mental health, so make an effort to connect with family, friends, and other supportive people.</li>
    <li>Practice self-care: Taking time for yourself, doing activities you enjoy, and practicing relaxation techniques can help improve mental health.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>If you are experiencing symptoms of a mental health disorder, it's important to seek help from a healthcare provider. They can help develop a personalized plan for managing your condition, which may include medications, therapy, or other treatments.</p>

